		<!-- message -->
		<div>Dephon-  What do I want you to prove?<br />
<br />
&quot;The problem with your numbers Varia, are how they are determined. If it is like most things politicians use to validate arguments, then they basically took surveys of the family members of anyone who died from lung cancer, heart disease, etc, then asked if those people that died had ever smoked. I'm sure they probably asked how often they smoked and other info, but where is the line drawn? how much smoking is considered attributed to smoking?&quot;<br />
<br />
I want you to prove that your inference that the data collection techniques are in fact flawed, or that the statistics and conclusions derived from that data are invalid, inapplicable or meaningless.  Remember, my series of posts has stemmed from the issue of &quot;4 million die each year&quot;, which is STRICTLY an issue of raw data and its handling.  Your paragraph I quoted is clearly  challenging the validity of the data gathering.  Prove your challenge with credible sources.<br />
<br />
Less than 1% of americans dont know its unhealthy?  I think its probably closer to 5-10% (excluding young children of course) but thats just a quibble really, and just my personal opinion in any case.  Oh I agree, I think that most people do &quot;know&quot; its unhealthy in an abstract kind of way, but I dispute that anything like as many really BELIEVE in their gut that its unhealthy before their mid 20's.  Its just something theyre sorta aware of, like they know that falling down is unhealthy, but its just not a big part of their life so they dont think about it much.  After all, all that nebulous &quot;bad stuff&quot; is a long way off in the distant future, and most young people dont think much about the future.  And young is when most people start smoking.  <br />
<br />
  I dont think that young people, especialy early teens, know that smoking is bad WELL ENOUGH to actually think about as part of some concious decision before they start smoking.  They drift into it through peer pressure related issues, or rebellion, or just curiousity to try the forbidden adult pleasures to see what theyre like.  They may &quot;know&quot; its bad, but i dont think they KNOW it.  Are you suggesting that all the future nastiness is really in peoples minds when they take that first drag?  And by the time people do start to realise how bad it might be, well, nicotine is addictive, ya know?....<br />
<br />
So I think education ads to drive it home earlier than it currently is is a good idea.  Now, whether the Truth series is effective at doing that or not is another issue entirely...  I personally think the &quot;this is your lung on cigs&quot; style is more effective, as I think that kind of thing has a bigger impact on the 10-15 age bracket, although I also think that a certain amount of the more cerebral and more emotional style ads are a good augment to that, if done credibly.  I havent seen many of the Truth series, but it does sound from the posts in this thread that they may be lacking in the credibility department.  But I think the principle is sound, even if this particular execution is flawed.<br />
<br />
And now I'm off to demonstrate the huge redeeming value I have for society at large by playing EQ!  :P<br />
<br />
Varia</div>
